"levels, avalanche problems, snowpack structure, and a season-wide map "
"timelapse, sourced from SLF."
msgstr ""

msgid "Snowdesk"
msgstr ""

msgid "Avalanche bulletins for backcountry skiers."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"We take the daily SLF avalanche forecast and present it in a clear, mobile-"
"friendly format so you can make better decisions in the mountains."
msgstr ""

msgid "Daily bulletins"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"fetched automatically from the Swiss Institute for Snow and Avalanche "
"Research (SLF)."
msgstr ""

msgid "Per-region detail"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"danger level, avalanche problems, snowpack structure, and field guidance for "
"every forecast region."
msgstr ""

msgid "Season at a glance"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"scrub through the whole season on the map to see how danger evolved across "
"regions."
msgstr ""

msgid "View a sample bulletin →"
msgstr ""

msgid "Explore the map →"
msgstr ""

msgid "How to read a bulletin"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"A guide to reading the SLF Swiss avalanche bulletin — danger levels, problem "
"types, elevation and aspect, and how the day evolves."
msgstr ""

msgid "How to read the avalanche bulletin"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Published daily by the WSL Institute for Snow and Avalanche Research (SLF), "
"the bulletin covers the Swiss Alps and Jura. It is an informed forecast — "
"not a guarantee — and cannot replace an on-site assessment. This guide "
"follows the same structure as the bulletin page itself: Day Risk Profile, "
"Avalanche Problems, and Snowpack &amp; Weather."
msgstr ""

msgid "The danger level"
msgstr ""

msgid "The bulletin uses the five-point European avalanche danger scale."
msgstr ""

msgid "Level 2 — moderate — as it appears on the bulletin day strip."
msgstr ""

#, python-format
msgid ""
"Danger increases disproportionately — the jump from level 2 to 3 is far more "
"significant than the numbers suggest. Around 50%% of avalanche fatalities "
"occur at level 3, 30%% at level 2."
msgstr ""

msgid "Level"
msgstr ""

msgid "Name"
msgstr ""

msgid "Characteristics"
msgstr ""

msgid "Low"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Generally favourable. Avalanches only in isolated cases on extremely steep "
"slopes."
msgstr ""

msgid "Moderate"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Mostly favourable. Avalanches possible on steep slopes with the indicated "
"aspects and elevation."
msgstr ""

msgid "Considerable"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Critical. Avalanches can be easily triggered on steep slopes; natural "
"avalanches and remote triggering possible."
msgstr ""

msgid "High"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Very critical. Natural avalanches likely; easily triggered on many steep "
"slopes."
msgstr ""

msgid "Very high"
msgstr ""

msgid "Extraordinary. Numerous very large natural avalanches expected."
msgstr ""

#, python-format
msgid ""
"In Swiss bulletin data covering October 2025 to May 2026, the distribution "
"across 2,159 bulletins was: low 20%%, moderate 54%%, considerable 35%%, high "
"5%%, very high &lt;1%%. (Some bulletins carry two danger levels for "
"different times of day; these percentages reflect the all-day rating.)"
msgstr ""

msgid "Subdivisions (–, =, +)"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"At level 2 and above with dry-snow danger, the SLF subdivides each level "
"into three positions: – (minus) towards the bottom, = (neutral) in the "
"middle, and + (plus) towards the top."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"3– — considerable danger towards the lower end of the level, sitting just "
"above the level 2/3 boundary."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"This reflects the fact that avalanche danger is a continuous spectrum, not a "
"step function. A rating of 3– sits just above the level 2/3 boundary; 3+ is "
"just below level 4."
msgstr ""

msgid "Subdivision only applies to dry-snow danger. It is never assigned to:"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Level 1 (low) — confirmed across all 2,159 bulletins in the dataset; not a "
"single low rating carries a subdivision"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Wet-snow hazards — wet snow and gliding snow are not assessed with "
"subdivisions"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"The afternoon period — the later danger rating is always wet, so subdivision "
"never appears there"
msgstr ""

msgid "A missing subdivision means \"not applicable\", not \"neutral\"."
msgstr ""

msgid "How the day evolves"
msgstr ""

#, python-format
msgid ""
"Most bulletins describe a single, stable hazard picture for the whole day. "
"In about 8%% of cases, a second danger level applies in the afternoon — "
"always wet snow or gliding snow, emerging as temperatures rise."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Considerable– all morning; moderate wet-snow risk developing later in the "
"afternoon."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"All bulletins where the afternoon differs from the morning involve wet snow "
"or gliding snow. Dry hazards never appear as a later-in-the-day entry — dry "
"snowpack problems are weather-independent within a single day, while wet "
"hazards are driven by daytime heating."
msgstr ""

msgid "Pattern"
msgstr ""

msgid "Frequency"
msgstr ""

msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

msgid "Dry only, all day"
msgstr ""

msgid "A single dry hazard with no wet component."
msgstr ""

msgid "Dry and wet simultaneously"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Both dry (above an elevation) and wet (below it) are active all day — often "
"after rain at lower elevations with new snow higher up."
msgstr ""

msgid "Dry all day, wet emerging later"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Morning is dominated by dry hazard; afternoon brings wet snow as "
"temperatures rise."
msgstr ""

msgid "Wet only, all day"
msgstr ""

msgid "No dry hazard — typically low-elevation regions or late spring."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"When the afternoon brings a higher danger level than the morning, timing is "
"critical: aim to complete exposed terrain before the snow softens. On east-"
"facing slopes this may mean before midday; on west-facing slopes it may be "
"mid-afternoon. The bulletin cannot pin down the exact transition time — it "
"depends on aspect, elevation, and conditions on the day."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"The bulletin assesses dry and wet avalanche hazards separately. These are "
"fundamentally different in cause, location, and behaviour."
msgstr ""

msgid "Dry avalanches"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Caused by structural weaknesses in the snowpack — new snow loading, wind-"
"deposited slabs, or persistent buried weak layers. Dry hazard is always "
"present throughout the day and always applies above a minimum elevation."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"New snow at moderate danger — widespread across all aspects above 1600m."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Persistent weak layers at considerable danger — shaded aspects above 2600m. "
"This hazard can remain active for weeks and avalanche-prone terrain is hard "
"to identify by eye."
msgstr ""

msgid "Problem type"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Recent snowfall loading the existing snowpack. Typically widespread across "
"all aspects."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Wind-deposited snow on leeward slopes, gullies, and bowls. Localised but "
"often hard to spot when buried."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Buried weak layers — faceted crystals, depth hoar, surface hoar — that can "
"remain reactive for weeks. Dangerous because avalanche-prone locations are "
"barely recognisable even to trained eyes. The dominant winter hazard."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"No clear dry hazard pattern. Not equivalent to no danger — any avalanche "
"type remains possible. Typically used at level 1."
msgstr ""

msgid "Wet avalanches"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Caused by liquid water weakening the snowpack, from melt or rain. The only "
"hazard type that is time-dependent — it can emerge or intensify as the day "
"warms."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Wet snow at moderate danger — E to W facing slopes below 2200m, emerging in "
"the afternoon as solar heating progresses."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Gliding snow at moderate danger — south-facing slopes below 1800m, active "
"all day. Release timing is unpredictable; glide cracks are a warning sign "
"but not a reliable predictor."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Snowpack weakened by melt or rain. Mainly natural avalanches. Solar "
"radiation and aspect determine which slopes are affected first. Timing is "
"critical — east-facing slopes warm earlier than west-facing ones."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"The entire snowpack slides on a smooth substrate (grass, rock). Almost "
"exclusively natural; human triggering is virtually impossible. Glide cracks "
"are a warning sign but release timing is unpredictable. Can occur at any "
"time of day, including overnight."
msgstr ""

msgid "Elevation and aspect"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Dry hazards apply above an elevation threshold; wet hazards apply below one "
"— the same boundary approached from opposite sides."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Wind slab: hazard above 2400m — dry problems always use a lower elevation "
"bound."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Wet snow: hazard below 2200m — wet problems always use an upper elevation "
"bound, marking the freeze-thaw or rain/snow line."
msgstr ""

msgid "Elevation"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"boundaries are approximate — conditions change gradually, not sharply. A "
"±200 m margin is reasonable. A slope near the boundary may sit in a "
"transition area where either the more or less favourable situation applies."
msgstr ""

msgid "Aspects"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"are compass directions of affected slopes. The convention is: a north-facing "
"slope falls to the north — you stand at the top, facing north, and the slope "
"drops away below you. North-facing slopes receive no direct solar radiation "
"in mid-winter; south-facing slopes receive regular sunshine year-round."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"When the bulletin cites specific aspects and an elevation, the stated danger "
"level applies to slopes satisfying both criteria. A common rule of thumb for "
"slopes outside the stated zone: assume one danger level lower. This is a "
"guideline, not a guarantee."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"When no aspects or elevation are given for a wet hazard, the danger is "
"region-wide and not spatially constrained."
msgstr ""

msgid "Multiple problem types"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"A single problem card can cite two problem types when both contribute to the "
"danger in the same area, at the same elevation, on the same aspects."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Wind slab and persistent weak layers sharing the same terrain — two labels, "
"one danger zone."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"They are two labels for one danger zone, not two independent hazards with "
"different locations. When two problem types are grouped together, they "
"always share identical spatial constraints and description text."
msgstr ""

#, python-format
msgid ""
"Multiple problem types within one card occur in around 47%% of bulletins. "
"The most common pairing is wind slab and persistent weak layers."
msgstr ""

msgid "Snowpack &amp; Weather"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Each bulletin includes four prose sections, updated once daily in the "
"evening. They expand on demand on the bulletin page."
msgstr ""

msgid "Snowpack"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Describes the layering and stability of the snowpack across the region. "
"Explains why the danger is as it is. Mentions observed avalanche activity. "
"Most directly useful for planning."
msgstr ""

msgid "Weather review"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Summarises what actually happened in the preceding period. Provides context "
"for why the snowpack is in its current state."
msgstr ""

msgid "Weather forecast"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Covers the next 24 hours: fresh snow amounts, temperature, wind. The danger "
"assessment is built on this forecast; if actual weather deviates, the danger "
"may differ."
msgstr ""

msgid "Outlook"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Indicative assessment for the two days after the bulletin's validity period. "
"Less detailed but useful for multi-day planning."
msgstr ""

msgid "Limitations"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"The bulletin is a regional forecast. It cannot assess individual slopes — it "
"can only indicate which types of terrain (aspect, elevation, steepness) "
"carry the indicated danger. Local conditions always require on-site "
"assessment."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Boundaries between regions, elevation bands, and aspects are gradual, not "
"sharp. A slope near the boundary of the stated zone may sit in a transition "
"area where either the more or less favourable situation applies."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"The bulletin applies exclusively to unsecured terrain away from prepared "
"pistes and marked ski runs."
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"Data findings in this document are derived from analysis of 2,159 Swiss "
"avalanche bulletins (October 2025 – May 2026) from the SLF CAAML API. "
"Definitions and qualitative descriptions are drawn from the SLF Avalanche "
"Bulletin Interpretation Guide, Edition November 2025."
msgstr ""

